const CHAPTERS_3_TO_8 = [
// ============================== CHAPTER 3: FORCE AND PRESSURE ==============================
{id:"c3n1",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"note",subtopic:"Definition of Force",content:`FORCE is the cause which changes (or tends to change) the state of rest or of uniform motion of a body, or changes its size or shape. It is a vector quantity (has both magnitude and direction). Forces are of two broad kinds: CONTACT forces (muscular, friction, normal, tension) and NON-CONTACT / field forces (gravitational, electrostatic, magnetic).`,explanation:`A force is a push or a pull that can start, stop, speed up, slow down or turn an object, or stretch/squash it. Because it has direction, two equal opposite forces can cancel out.`,teacherTip:`Force = push or pull. Always state a direction with it.`,examTip:`Mention that force can change BOTH the "state of motion" AND the "shape" of an object.`},
{id:"c3n2",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"note",subtopic:"Weight and Mass",content:`MASS is the quantity of matter in a body; it is constant everywhere and is a scalar (unit: kg). WEIGHT is the force with which a body is attracted towards the centre of the Earth; W = mg; it is a vector (unit: newton, N) and CHANGES with location because g changes. On the Moon g is about 1/6 of Earth's, so weight there is 1/6, although mass is unchanged.`,explanation:`Mass is "how much stuff" you are made of, which never changes. Weight is the gravitational pull on that mass, so you weigh less on the Moon even though your mass is the same.`,teacherTip:`Mass = constant; weight = "moody" (depends on g).`,examTip:`Remember W = m x g, and state that mass is scalar while weight is a vector.`},
{id:"c3n3",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"note",subtopic:"Units of Force",content:`The S.I. unit of force is the NEWTON (N). One newton is the force which, acting on a body of mass 1 kg, produces an ACCELERATION of 1 m/s2 (from Newton's second law, F = m x a, so 1 N = 1 kg.m/s2). A gravitational unit is the kilogram-force: 1 kgf = 9.8 N ≈ 10 N (the weight of a 1 kg mass).`,explanation:`Force is measured by the acceleration it produces on a known mass. One newton is roughly the weight of a small (≈100 g) apple. 1 kgf is the pull of gravity on 1 kg.`,teacherTip:`1 N = 1 kg.m/s2. Multiply kgf by ~10 to get newtons.`,examTip:`Write the unit as capital "N". Define 1 N using acceleration (1 m/s2), NOT speed.`},
{id:"c3n4",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"note",subtopic:"Rigid and Non-Rigid Bodies",content:`A RIGID body does not change its shape or size when a force is applied — the force can only change its state of motion (e.g. a stone, a brick). A NON-RIGID (deformable) body changes its shape/size under force as well as (possibly) its motion (e.g. a sponge, rubber, dough, a spring).`,explanation:`A rigid body is like a brick that won't bend. A non-rigid body is like a sponge or spring that deforms when squeezed or stretched.`,teacherTip:`Rigid = keeps shape. Non-rigid = deforms.`,examTip:`For non-rigid bodies, force can cause BOTH motion AND deformation.`},
{id:"c3n5",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"note",subtopic:"Turning Effect / Moment of Force",content:`The TURNING EFFECT (MOMENT) of a force about a point/axis = Force x perpendicular distance of the line of action of the force from the pivot. Moment = F x d. S.I. unit = newton metre (N m). The greater the perpendicular distance, the greater the turning effect for the same force.`,explanation:`This is what makes a door swing on its hinges. Pushing far from the hinge (large d) produces a larger moment, so the door turns more easily.`,teacherTip:`Moment = how hard x how far (perpendicular).`,examTip:`The distance must be PERPENDICULAR (at 90 degrees) to the force.`},
{id:"c3n6",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"note",subtopic:"Thrust and Pressure",content:`THRUST is the force acting normally (perpendicularly) on a surface; it is a force, so its unit is the newton (N). PRESSURE is thrust per unit area: P = Thrust / Area = F/A. S.I. unit = pascal (Pa) = N m^-2. For the same thrust, a SMALLER area gives a LARGER pressure (sharp knife, needle); a LARGER area gives a SMALLER pressure (camel's broad feet, snow shoes, wide tractor tyres).`,explanation:`Pressure tells how concentrated a force is. A sharp needle has high pressure because all the force acts over a tiny area.`,teacherTip:`Pressure = force's "concentration" on a surface.`,examTip:`Give both units: N m^-2 and pascal (Pa). Pressure ∝ 1/Area for fixed thrust.`},
{id:"c3n7",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"note",subtopic:"Atmospheric Pressure",content:`ATMOSPHERIC PRESSURE is the pressure exerted by the weight of the column of air above us. At sea level, 1 atm = 76 cm of mercury (Hg) = 1.013 x 10^5 Pa. It is measured by a BAROMETER. Atmospheric pressure DECREASES with altitude (the air column above gets shorter and thinner). Many everyday actions (drinking with a straw, syringes, suction hooks, rubber suckers) work because of atmospheric pressure.`,explanation:`A tall column of air presses on everything from above. We don't feel crushed because our body fluids push outward with equal pressure.`,teacherTip:`A barometer measures atmospheric pressure; mercury is used because it is very dense.`,examTip:`Remember 1 atm = 76 cm Hg = 1.013 x 10^5 Pa.`},
{id:"c3n8",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"note",subtopic:"Liquid Pressure",content:`Pressure at depth h inside a liquid: P = h x d x g (d = density of the liquid, g = acceleration due to gravity). Liquid pressure: (i) increases with DEPTH, (ii) increases with DENSITY, (iii) acts EQUALLY in all directions at a given depth, and (iv) does NOT depend on the area or shape of the container. A liquid finds its own level in connected vessels.`,explanation:`The deeper you dive, the more liquid is above you, so the greater the pressure. Mercury, being denser, gives more pressure than water at the same depth.`,teacherTip:`Deep = high pressure; dense liquid = high pressure.`,examTip:`P = h x d x g. Note that pressure does NOT depend on container shape/area.`},
{id:"c3n9",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"note",subtopic:"NEET Bridge — Newton's Laws, Pascal & Buoyancy",content:`The force ideas here lead straight into NEWTON'S LAWS of motion (NEET core): 1st (inertia), 2nd (F = ma — the very basis of "1 newton"), 3rd (action-reaction). Liquid pressure leads to PASCAL'S LAW (pressure applied to an enclosed fluid is transmitted equally — the principle of the HYDRAULIC press/brakes/lift) and to ARCHIMEDES' PRINCIPLE / BUOYANCY (an object in a fluid feels an upthrust equal to the weight of fluid displaced — why ships float and we feel lighter in water). Note: F = ma also means weight W = mg is just the special case of force = mass x (gravitational acceleration g).`,explanation:`"1 N = force giving 1 kg an acceleration of 1 m/s2" is literally Newton's second law in disguise. Hydraulics and floating both come from how pressure behaves in fluids.`,teacherTip:`Hydraulic lift = Pascal's law; floating = Archimedes' upthrust.`,examTip:`NEET: F = ma; Pascal's law -> hydraulic machines; upthrust = weight of fluid displaced.`},
{id:"c3tf1",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The S.I. unit of force is kgf.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. The S.I. unit of force is the newton (N). kgf (kilogram-force) is a gravitational unit, not an S.I. unit.`,teacherTip:`S.I. unit = newton; kgf is a non-S.I. gravitational unit.`,examTip:`1 kgf ≈ 9.8 N.`},
{id:"c3tf2",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"A force always produces both linear and turning motions.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. A force produces turning motion only if the body is pivoted (free to rotate). A free body simply undergoes linear motion.`,teacherTip:`Turning needs a pivot.`,examTip:`The word "always" in a T/F statement often signals it is false.`},
{id:"c3tf3",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Moment of force = force x perpendicular distance from the pivot.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. Both the magnitude of the force and its perpendicular distance from the pivot decide the turning effect.`,teacherTip:`This is why a door opens more easily when pushed near the handle.`,examTip:`Include the word "perpendicular" in your definition.`},
{id:"c3tf4",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Less force is needed when applied at a farther distance from the pivot.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. A larger perpendicular distance gives a larger moment, so less force is needed to produce the same turning effect (the lever/spanner principle).`,teacherTip:`More distance = less effort for the same turn.`,examTip:`This is why spanners and door handles have long arms.`},
{id:"c3tf5",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"For a given thrust, pressure is more on a surface of large area.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. For a given thrust, pressure is LESS on a larger area. P = F/A, so larger A -> smaller P.`,teacherTip:`Big area = gentle pressure; small area = sharp pressure.`,examTip:`Pressure is inversely proportional to area for a fixed thrust.`},
{id:"c3tf6",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The S.I. unit of pressure is pascal.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. 1 pascal (Pa) = 1 N/m2. It is named after Blaise Pascal.`,teacherTip:`Pascal is the S.I. unit of pressure.`,examTip:`Be ready to define 1 Pa as 1 N/m2.`},
{id:"c3tf7",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"A liquid exerts pressure in all directions.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. Unlike solids (which press only downward), a liquid presses on every surface it touches, equally in all directions at a given depth.`,teacherTip:`Under water, pressure pushes on your ears from all sides.`,examTip:`This is a fundamental property of fluids.`},
{id:"c3tf8",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Higher we go, the greater is the air pressure.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Atmospheric pressure DECREASES with altitude because the column of air above becomes shorter and thinner.`,teacherTip:`Higher altitude = less air above = lower pressure.`,examTip:`Pressure and altitude have an inverse relationship.`},
{id:"c3tf9",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Liquid pressure at a given depth depends on the shape of the container.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Liquid pressure depends only on depth (h), density (d) and g — NOT on the shape or area of the container. At equal depths, pressure is equal in differently shaped vessels.`,teacherTip:`P = hdg has no "shape" or "area" term.`,examTip:`Connected vessels show liquid reaching the same level regardless of shape.`},
{id:"c3fb1",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"1 kgf = ______ N (nearly).",blankAnswer:"10",answer:`1 kgf = 10 N (nearly). The exact value is 9.8 N.`,teacherTip:`kgf = kilogram-force ≈ 10 N.`,examTip:`Use 10 N only when the question says "nearly/approximately".`},
{id:"c3fb2",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Moment of force = ______ x perpendicular distance from the pivot.",blankAnswer:"force",answer:`Moment of force = force x perpendicular distance from the pivot.`,teacherTip:`This is why a heavy gate opens more easily when pushed at its edge.`,examTip:`Measure the distance in metres for S.I. units.`},
{id:"c3fb3",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"In a door, the handle is provided ______ from the hinges.",blankAnswer:"farthest",answer:`The handle is placed farthest from the hinges to maximise the turning effect (moment) with the least force.`,teacherTip:`Maximum distance = minimum effort.`,examTip:`Use "lever arm" / "perpendicular distance" to explain the design.`},
{id:"c3fb4",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The S.I. unit of pressure is ______.",blankAnswer:"pascal",answer:`The S.I. unit of pressure is the pascal (Pa); 1 Pa = 1 N/m2.`,teacherTip:`1 Pa is a very small pressure.`,examTip:`Symbol is "Pa" — capital P, small a.`},
{id:"c3fb5",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Pressure in a liquid ______ with depth.",blankAnswer:"increases",answer:`Pressure in a liquid increases with depth (P = h x d x g).`,teacherTip:`Like a human pyramid — the bottom feels the most pressure.`,examTip:`Liquid pressure depends on depth (h) and density (d).`},
{id:"c3fb6",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The instrument used to measure atmospheric pressure is the ______.",blankAnswer:"barometer",answer:`The barometer measures atmospheric pressure (a mercury barometer reads about 76 cm Hg at sea level).`,teacherTip:`Baro = pressure, meter = measure.`,examTip:`A falling barometer reading can indicate an approaching storm.`},
{id:"c3m1",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"match",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Match Column A with Column B",pairs:[{left:"Camel",right:"broad feet (low pressure)"},{left:"Truck",right:"six or eight tyres"},{left:"Knife",right:"sharp cutting edge"},{left:"Thrust",right:"newton (N)"},{left:"Moment of force",right:"N m"},{left:"Atmospheric pressure",right:"76 cm Hg"}],answer:`Camel->broad feet (low pressure), Truck->six or eight tyres, Knife->sharp cutting edge, Thrust->N, Moment of force->N m, Atmospheric pressure->76 cm Hg.`,teacherTip:`Match each design to the pressure principle it uses.`,examTip:`Write full correct pairs clearly.`},
{id:"c3mcq1",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The S.I. unit of moment of force is:",options:["N","N m^-2","kgf","N m"],correctOption:3,answer:`N m. Since moment = force (N) x distance (m), the unit is the newton-metre (N m).`,teacherTip:`Moment = force x distance, so unit = N x m.`,examTip:`Do not confuse N m (moment) with N/m or N m^-2 (pressure).`},
{id:"c3mcq2",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The unit of pressure is:",options:["N","kgf","N m^-2","N m"],correctOption:2,answer:`N m^-2 (= pascal). Pressure = force / area.`,teacherTip:`The ^-2 exponent means "per square metre".`,examTip:`N m^-2 and Pa are identical.`},
{id:"c3mcq3",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Pressure and thrust are related as:",options:["Pressure = Thrust x Area","Thrust = Pressure / Area","Pressure = Thrust / Area","Pressure = Area / Thrust"],correctOption:2,answer:`Pressure = Thrust / Area — the fundamental formula of the chapter.`,teacherTip:`Pressure is the "average push" on each unit of surface.`,examTip:`Rearranged: Thrust = Pressure x Area.`},
{id:"c3mcq4",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The atmospheric pressure at sea level is nearly:",options:["10 Pa","100,000 Pa","1000 Pa","10,000 Pa"],correctOption:1,answer:`100,000 Pa (≈ 1.013 x 10^5 Pa) — the standard sea-level atmospheric pressure.`,teacherTip:`10^5 is a short way to write 100,000.`,examTip:`Accept 10^5 Pa or 100,000 Pa — they are the same.`},
{id:"c3mcq5",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Numerical",question:"A force of 200 N acts on an area of 4 m2. The pressure exerted is:",options:["800 Pa","50 Pa","204 Pa","0.02 Pa"],correctOption:1,answer:`P = F/A = 200 N / 4 m2 = 50 Pa.`,teacherTip:`Divide force by area; keep units S.I.`,examTip:`Always state the unit (Pa) in your final answer.`},
{id:"c3mcq6",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Numerical",question:"A force of 20 N acts at a perpendicular distance of 0.5 m from a pivot. The moment of force is:",options:["40 N m","10 N m","20.5 N m","0.025 N m"],correctOption:1,answer:`Moment = F x d = 20 N x 0.5 m = 10 N m.`,teacherTip:`Multiply force by perpendicular distance.`,examTip:`Distance must be perpendicular and in metres.`},
{id:"c3ar1",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Assertion-Reason",question:"Assertion (A): It is easier to cut with a sharp knife than a blunt one. Reason (R): A sharp edge has a smaller area, so the same force produces greater pressure.",options:["Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true, but R is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true"],correctOption:0,answer:`Both true and R explains A. P = F/A; a sharp edge has a tiny area, so the same force gives a much larger pressure, cutting more easily.`,teacherTip:`Smaller area -> larger pressure for the same force.`,examTip:`Use P = F/A to justify everyday "sharp vs blunt" cases.`},
{id:"c3sa1",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Define force. State its S.I. unit.",answer:`Force is a physical cause that changes, or tends to change, the state of rest or the state of uniform motion of a body (and can also change its shape/size). The S.I. unit of force is the newton (N), where 1 N = 1 kg.m/s2.`,teacherTip:`Force = push or pull, with direction.`,examTip:`Include "tends to change" to cover balanced forces that cause no actual movement.`},
{id:"c3sa2",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"State two effects of a force when applied on a body.",answer:`(i) It can change the state of motion — start, stop, speed up, slow down or change the direction of a body.\n(ii) It can change the shape and size of a body (e.g. stretching a spring, squashing a sponge).`,teacherTip:`Think "Motion" and "Makeover (shape)".`,examTip:`Use clear examples like "stopping a ball" and "stretching a spring".`},
{id:"c3sa3",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Define moment of force. State its S.I. unit and two factors affecting it.",answer:`Moment of force is the turning effect of a force about an axis or pivot.\nMoment = force x perpendicular distance from the axis.\nS.I. unit: N m (newton-metre).\nFactors: (i) magnitude of the force, (ii) perpendicular distance of the line of action of the force from the axis.`,teacherTip:`Moment of force = scientific name for "turning power".`,examTip:`Always relate it to an axis/pivot, and use the perpendicular distance.`},
{id:"c3sa4",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Define pressure. State its S.I. unit and formula.",answer:`Pressure is the thrust (force) acting perpendicularly per unit area of a surface.\nP = F/A (thrust / area).\nS.I. unit: pascal (Pa) = N m^-2.`,teacherTip:`Pressure is like "force density" on a surface.`,examTip:`Give both N m^-2 and pascal (Pa) as equivalent units.`},
{id:"c3sa5",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"State two factors affecting pressure. Give examples.",answer:`(i) Area of contact: greater area -> lesser pressure (e.g. a camel's broad feet stop it sinking in sand; wide tractor tyres).\n(ii) Magnitude of thrust: greater thrust -> greater pressure.\nAlso: a sharp knife/needle cuts easily because the small contact area gives very high pressure.`,teacherTip:`Sharp = small area = high pressure.`,examTip:`Use "inversely proportional to area" and "directly proportional to thrust".`},
{id:"c3sa6",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"State three factors affecting liquid pressure. Give the formula.",answer:`Liquid pressure P = h x d x g\nFactors:\n(i) Depth/height of the liquid column (h) — increases with depth.\n(ii) Density of the liquid (d) — denser liquid gives more pressure.\n(iii) Acceleration due to gravity (g).\nIt does NOT depend on the area or shape of the container.`,teacherTip:`Deep = high pressure; dense = high pressure.`,examTip:`Remember P = h x d x g and the "no shape dependence" point.`},
{id:"c3sa7",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"HOTS / Application",question:"Why does nose bleeding sometimes occur at high altitudes?",answer:`At high altitudes the atmospheric (external) pressure is low. The blood pressure inside the body, however, stays high. This makes the internal blood pressure greater than the external atmospheric pressure.\n\nThe excess internal pressure can rupture the thin, delicate blood vessels (capillaries) in the nose, causing a nose bleed.\n\nIn short: low external pressure + normal internal pressure -> large pressure difference -> capillaries burst.`,teacherTip:`Internal blood pressure exceeds the reduced outside air pressure.`,examTip:`Explain via the pressure DIFFERENCE between inside the body and the thin outside air.`},
{id:"c3sa8",topicId:"ch3-force",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"HOTS / Application",question:"Explain how a hydraulic press lets a small force lift a heavy load, naming the principle used.",answer:`A hydraulic press works on PASCAL'S LAW: pressure applied to an enclosed liquid is transmitted equally and undiminished in all directions.\n\nA small force F1 is applied on a small piston of area A1, creating a pressure P = F1/A1. This same pressure acts on a large piston of area A2, producing a force F2 = P x A2 = F1 x (A2/A1).\n\nBecause A2 is much larger than A1, the output force F2 is much greater than the input force F1 — so a small effort lifts a heavy load. Used in hydraulic lifts, jacks and car brakes.`,teacherTip:`Same pressure on a bigger area = bigger force.`,examTip:`Name Pascal's law and show F2 = F1 x (A2/A1).`},
// ============================== CHAPTER 4: ENERGY ==============================
{id:"c4n1",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"note",subtopic:"Work - Definition & Formula",content:`WORK is done when a force applied on a body produces a displacement in the direction of the force. W = F x d (more generally W = F x d x cos(theta), where theta is the angle between force and displacement). S.I. unit = joule (J); 1 J = 1 N x 1 m. Work is a scalar quantity.`,explanation:`Work transfers energy through motion. If there is no displacement (pushing a wall) or the displacement is at right angles to the force, no work is done.`,teacherTip:`No movement = no work, no matter the effort!`,examTip:`Explain that displacement is zero when pushing an immovable wall, so W = 0.`},
{id:"c4n2",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"note",subtopic:"Conditions for Zero Work",content:`No work is done when: (i) there is NO displacement (s = 0), e.g. pushing a wall that does not move; (ii) the displacement is PERPENDICULAR to the force (theta = 90 degrees, so cos(theta) = 0), e.g. a coolie walking on level ground with a load on his head — the force (vertical) is at right angles to the motion (horizontal); (iii) NO force acts (a body moving at constant velocity in free space).`,explanation:`A coolie carrying a box on his head along a level road does no work against gravity because the lifting force is vertical while the motion is horizontal (angle 90 degrees).`,teacherTip:`Push "up" while moving "forward" = zero work on the load.`,examTip:`State that the angle between force and displacement is 90 degrees (cos 90 = 0).`},
{id:"c4n3",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"note",subtopic:"Energy - Definition",content:`ENERGY is the capacity to do work. Its S.I. unit is the joule (J) — the same unit as work, because energy is "stored work". Energy exists in many forms: mechanical (kinetic + potential), heat, light, sound, electrical, chemical and nuclear, and one form can transform into another.`,explanation:`Energy is like a "bank balance" that lets an object do work. Since work and energy are interchangeable, they share the same unit, the joule.`,teacherTip:`Energy is the "fuel" needed to do work.`,examTip:`"Capacity to do work" is the standard definition of energy.`},
{id:"c4n4",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"note",subtopic:"Mechanical Energy: PE and KE",content:`MECHANICAL ENERGY = Potential Energy (PE) + Kinetic Energy (KE).\nPOTENTIAL ENERGY: energy due to position or shape; gravitational PE = mgh.\nKINETIC ENERGY: energy due to motion; KE = (1/2)mv^2.\nLAW OF CONSERVATION OF ENERGY: energy can neither be created nor destroyed, only transformed; the total mechanical energy of a freely falling body stays constant (PE -> KE).`,explanation:`PE is stored energy (a book on a shelf, a stretched spring). KE is energy of motion (a rolling ball). As a body falls, PE converts into KE while the total stays the same.`,teacherTip:`PE and KE are two sides of the same mechanical coin.`,examTip:`When a body falls: PE decreases, KE increases, total (PE + KE) is constant.`},
{id:"c4n5",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"note",subtopic:"Power",content:`POWER is the rate of doing work (or rate of using energy). P = W/t. S.I. unit = watt (W) = J/s. Larger units: kilowatt (1 kW = 1000 W) and horsepower (1 H.P. = 746 W). A more powerful machine does the same work in less time.`,explanation:`Power measures how FAST work is done. Two motors may do the same work, but the one that does it quicker is more powerful.`,teacherTip:`Power = "work with a stopwatch".`,examTip:`Use P = W/t; ensure time is in seconds for the answer in watts.`},
{id:"c4n6",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"note",subtopic:"NEET Bridge — Work-Energy Theorem & Conservation",content:`In Class 11/NEET, W = F.d generalises to W = F.d.cos(theta) (a dot product), and the WORK-ENERGY THEOREM states: net work done on a body = change in its kinetic energy (W = change in KE = (1/2)mv^2 - (1/2)mu^2). The LAW OF CONSERVATION OF ENERGY underlies all physics: e.g. in a pendulum or roller-coaster, PE and KE swap continuously while the total stays constant (ignoring friction). Note KE is proportional to v^2, so doubling speed quadruples KE — a key reason vehicle braking distance rises sharply with speed (road-safety physics).`,explanation:`The "no work if theta = 90" rule and the PE<->KE swapping you see now become the formal work-energy theorem and energy conservation that dominate NEET mechanics.`,teacherTip:`Net work = change in KE (work-energy theorem).`,examTip:`NEET: W = change in KE; total energy is always conserved.`},
{id:"c4tf1",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"A coolie does no work against gravity while carrying luggage on a level road.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. The motion is horizontal while the gravitational force is vertical — the angle is 90 degrees, so work done against gravity is zero (cos 90 = 0).`,teacherTip:`Force and motion must be in the same line for work to be done.`,examTip:`State the angle is 90 degrees between force and displacement.`},
{id:"c4tf2",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The energy stored in the water of a dam is kinetic energy.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Water held high in a dam is (mostly) at rest at a height, so it has gravitational POTENTIAL energy (mgh). It converts to kinetic energy only when it flows down.`,teacherTip:`Stored at a height = potential energy.`,examTip:`If water is "stored/still", the answer is potential energy.`},
{id:"c4tf3",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Work done by a boy depends on the time in which he does the work.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Work depends only on force and displacement (W = F x d), not on time. Time enters only when calculating POWER.`,teacherTip:`Work ignores the clock; power does not.`,examTip:`Do NOT include time in the formula for work.`},
{id:"c4tf4",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Power spent by a body depends on the time for which it does work.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. Power = Work / Time. For a given amount of work, doing it in less time means more power.`,teacherTip:`Power = speedy work.`,examTip:`For fixed work, power is inversely proportional to time.`},
{id:"c4tf5",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"If the speed of a body is doubled, its kinetic energy also just doubles.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. KE = (1/2)mv^2, so KE depends on v^2. Doubling the speed makes KE FOUR times as large, not double.`,teacherTip:`v is squared in KE.`,examTip:`Triple the speed -> KE becomes 9 times.`},
{id:"c4fb1",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Work done = Force x ______.",blankAnswer:"distance",answer:`Work done = Force x distance moved in the direction of the force.`,teacherTip:`Direction matters — force and motion must be along the same line.`,examTip:`Memorise W = F x d.`},
{id:"c4fb2",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The S.I. unit of energy is ______.",blankAnswer:"joule",answer:`The S.I. unit of energy is the joule (J), the same as the unit of work.`,teacherTip:`Joule is the common "currency" for work and energy.`,examTip:`1 J = 1 N x 1 m.`},
{id:"c4fb3",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Kinetic energy = (1/2) x mass x ______.",blankAnswer:"(speed)^2",answer:`Kinetic energy = (1/2) x mass x (speed)^2. Because speed is squared, doubling the speed quadruples the KE.`,teacherTip:`Speed has a much bigger effect on KE than mass does.`,examTip:`Don't forget the "1/2" and the "squared".`},
{id:"c4fb4",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"1 H.P. = ______ W.",blankAnswer:"746",answer:`1 horsepower (H.P.) = 746 watts.`,teacherTip:`746 is the magic number for H.P. -> watts.`,examTip:`Memorise this value for conversion questions.`},
{id:"c4fb5",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Energy can neither be created nor destroyed — this is the law of ______ of energy.",blankAnswer:"conservation",answer:`The Law of Conservation of Energy — energy only transforms from one form to another; the total remains constant.`,teacherTip:`Energy is recycled, never lost.`,examTip:`Use a falling body (PE->KE) as a supporting example.`},
{id:"c4m1",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"match",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Match Column A with Column B",pairs:[{left:"A stone at a height",right:"potential energy"},{left:"A moving ball",right:"kinetic energy"},{left:"Energy",right:"joule"},{left:"Power",right:"work done in 1 s"},{left:"watt",right:"unit of power"}],answer:`Stone at a height->potential energy, Moving ball->kinetic energy, Energy->joule, Power->work done in 1 s, watt->unit of power.`,teacherTip:`Match objects to their energy type and quantities to their units.`,examTip:`Draw clean straight lines for matching.`},
{id:"c4mcq1",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The S.I. unit of work is:",options:["second","metre","joule","newton"],correctOption:2,answer:`Joule (J). Work and energy share the joule as their S.I. unit.`,teacherTip:`Joule = work/energy.`,examTip:`Don't pick newton (that's force).`},
{id:"c4mcq2",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"No work is done by a force if the body:",options:["moves in the direction of force","does not move","moves in the opposite direction","none of these"],correctOption:1,answer:`Does not move. If displacement = 0, then W = F x d = 0.`,teacherTip:`Static body = zero work.`,examTip:`"No work" usually means "no displacement" (or theta = 90).`},
{id:"c4mcq3",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"When a boy doubles his speed, his kinetic energy becomes:",options:["half","double","four times","unchanged"],correctOption:2,answer:`Four times. KE = (1/2)mv^2; doubling v gives (2v)^2 = 4v^2, so KE becomes 4 times.`,teacherTip:`Double speed = quadruple energy.`,examTip:`Use the v^2 dependence to explain.`},
{id:"c4mcq4",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"A boy lifts a load from a height of 2 m to 4 m. Its potential energy becomes:",options:["half","double","one-third","one-fourth"],correctOption:1,answer:`Double. PE = mgh is directly proportional to height; 4 m is twice 2 m, so PE doubles.`,teacherTip:`Double the height -> double the PE.`,examTip:`Heights and PE follow the same ratio when mass is constant.`},
{id:"c4mcq5",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Numerical",question:"A force of 10 N moves a body 5 m in its own direction. The work done is:",options:["2 J","15 J","50 J","0.5 J"],correctOption:2,answer:`W = F x d = 10 N x 5 m = 50 J.`,teacherTip:`Multiply force by displacement (same direction).`,examTip:`State the unit (J).`},
{id:"c4mcq6",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Numerical",question:"A machine does 600 J of work in 30 s. Its power is:",options:["20 W","18000 W","630 W","0.05 W"],correctOption:0,answer:`P = W/t = 600 J / 30 s = 20 W.`,teacherTip:`Divide work by time (in seconds).`,examTip:`Answer in watts when time is in seconds.`},
{id:"c4ar1",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Assertion-Reason",question:"Assertion (A): A body moving in a circular path at constant speed has no work done on it by the centripetal force. Reason (R): The centripetal force is always perpendicular to the displacement.",options:["Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true, but R is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true"],correctOption:0,answer:`Both true and R explains A. The centripetal force points to the centre while the motion is along the circle (tangential); they are perpendicular (theta = 90, cos = 0), so the work done is zero.`,teacherTip:`Perpendicular force does no work.`,examTip:`Connect "perpendicular" to W = Fd cos(theta) = 0.`},
{id:"c4sa1",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Define work. State two conditions when no work is done.",answer:`Work is done when a force applied on a body causes displacement in the direction of the force. W = F x d.\n\nNo work is done when:\n(i) The displacement is zero (s = 0), e.g. pushing a wall that doesn't move.\n(ii) The displacement is perpendicular to the force (theta = 90 degrees), e.g. a coolie walking on level ground with a load on his head.`,teacherTip:`Zero movement OR a 90-degree angle = zero work.`,examTip:`List both conditions separately for full marks.`},
{id:"c4sa2",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Define energy. What are the two kinds of mechanical energy?",answer:`ENERGY: the capacity to do work. S.I. unit = joule (J).\n\nTwo kinds of mechanical energy:\n(i) Potential energy (PE) — energy due to position or shape (PE = mgh).\n(ii) Kinetic energy (KE) — energy due to motion (KE = (1/2)mv^2).\n\nMechanical energy = PE + KE.`,teacherTip:`PE = Place/Position; KE = Kick/Motion.`,examTip:`Mention both PE and KE as the components of mechanical energy.`},
{id:"c4sa3",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Write the expressions for PE and KE, explaining the symbols used.",answer:`PE = mgh, where m = mass, g = acceleration due to gravity, h = height above the reference level.\n\nKE = (1/2)mv^2, where m = mass, v = speed/velocity.\n\nPE depends on mass and height; KE depends on mass and the SQUARE of speed (so speed matters a lot).`,teacherTip:`PE likes height; KE loves speed (squared).`,examTip:`Label each symbol clearly.`},
{id:"c4sa4",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Define power. State its S.I. unit. What is 1 H.P.?",answer:`Power is the rate of doing work (or rate of transfer of energy). P = W/t = (F x d)/t.\nS.I. unit: watt (W) = J/s.\n1 H.P. (horsepower) = 746 W.`,teacherTip:`1 watt = 1 joule per second.`,examTip:`Use P = W/t with time in seconds.`},
{id:"c4sa5",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Name the type of energy: (a) moving cricket ball (b) stone on a building top (c) compressed spring (d) stretched rubber band (e) water flowing in a river.",answer:`(a) Moving cricket ball — Kinetic energy (due to motion).\n(b) Stone on a building top — Potential energy (due to height).\n(c) Compressed spring — Potential energy (elastic PE due to changed shape).\n(d) Stretched rubber band — Potential energy (elastic PE due to stretching).\n(e) Water flowing in a river — Kinetic energy (due to motion).`,teacherTip:`Motion = kinetic; height/stretching/compression = potential.`,examTip:`Add the brief reason beside each answer.`},
{id:"c4sa6",topicId:"ch4-energy",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"HOTS / Application",question:"Describe the energy changes when a ball is dropped from a height and bounces back (assume small losses).",answer:`At the top (before falling): the ball has maximum gravitational POTENTIAL energy (mgh) and zero kinetic energy.\n\nWhile falling: PE decreases and KE increases — PE is converted into KE. Just before hitting the ground, almost all energy is KINETIC (maximum speed).\n\nAt impact: the ball deforms, so KE is briefly stored as ELASTIC potential energy in the squashed ball; some energy is lost as heat and sound.\n\nDuring the bounce up: the elastic PE pushes the ball up, converting back to KE and then to gravitational PE as it rises.\n\nBecause some energy is lost as heat/sound each bounce, the ball rises a little less each time — but total energy is always conserved (it just changes form).`,teacherTip:`Track PE <-> KE <-> elastic PE, with small losses to heat/sound.`,examTip:`State the conservation of energy and where the "lost" energy goes.`},
// ============================== CHAPTER 5: LIGHT ENERGY ==============================
{id:"c5n1",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"note",subtopic:"Nature of Light",content:`Light is a form of energy that produces the sensation of sight. It travels in straight lines (rectilinear propagation) and needs NO medium (it travels through vacuum). Speed in vacuum/air = 3 x 10^8 m/s; it slows in denser media: water ≈ 2.25 x 10^8 m/s, glass ≈ 2 x 10^8 m/s.`,explanation:`Light is fastest in vacuum and slows in denser materials. Its straight-line travel is why shadows and eclipses form.`,teacherTip:`Denser medium (gas->liquid->solid) -> slower light.`,examTip:`Memorise the speed of light in air: 3 x 10^8 m/s.`},
{id:"c5n2",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"note",subtopic:"Refraction of Light",content:`REFRACTION is the change in direction (bending) of light when it passes from one transparent medium into another, caused by a change in its speed. Rule: going RARER -> DENSER, light bends TOWARDS the normal (slows down); going DENSER -> RARER, light bends AWAY from the normal (speeds up). A ray hitting the surface along the normal (angle of incidence 0) passes straight through, unbent.`,explanation:`Light bends because it changes speed at the boundary, like a car's wheels turning when one side hits sand. Refraction is why a straw looks bent in a glass of water.`,teacherTip:`Mnemonic "DRA": Denser->Rarer = Away from normal.`,examTip:`Both media must be transparent for refraction to be observed.`},
{id:"c5n3",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"note",subtopic:"Laws of Refraction (Snell's Law)",content:`(i) The incident ray, the refracted ray and the normal at the point of incidence all lie in the SAME plane.\n(ii) sin(i) / sin(r) = constant = refractive index (mu) for the given pair of media (Snell's Law).\nRefractive index mu = (speed of light in air) / (speed in medium) = (real depth) / (apparent depth). Higher mu -> denser medium -> slower light. mu(water) ≈ 1.33, mu(glass) ≈ 1.5.`,explanation:`The ratio of the sines of the angles is fixed for two media. A larger refractive index means the medium slows light more (optically denser).`,teacherTip:`mu(water) = 1.33, mu(glass) = 1.5.`,examTip:`Use mu = sin(i)/sin(r) for calculations; also mu = real depth/apparent depth.`},
{id:"c5n4",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"note",subtopic:"Dispersion of Light",content:`DISPERSION is the splitting of white light into its seven constituent colours (VIBGYOR: Violet, Indigo, Blue, Green, Yellow, Orange, Red) on passing through a prism. White light is a mixture of these colours; in glass, VIOLET travels slowest (bends the most) and RED travels fastest (bends the least). A rainbow is natural dispersion by water droplets.`,explanation:`Each colour has a slightly different speed (and refractive index) in glass, so each bends by a different amount and the colours fan out.`,teacherTip:`Rainbows are dispersion by raindrops.`,examTip:`Violet bends MOST, red bends LEAST.`},
{id:"c5n5",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"note",subtopic:"Spherical Mirrors",content:`A CONCAVE mirror CONVERGES light; depending on the object's position it forms a real or virtual image (used as shaving/make-up mirrors, in torches, headlights and solar cookers). A CONVEX mirror DIVERGES light and ALWAYS forms a virtual, erect, diminished image with a wide field of view (used as a rear-view/driving mirror and in shops). For both, focal length f = R/2 (R = radius of curvature).`,explanation:`A concave mirror "caves in" and focuses light to a point; a convex mirror "bulges out" and spreads light, showing a wider but smaller view.`,teacherTip:`Concave = "cave in" (converges); convex = "bulge out" (diverges).`,examTip:`f = R/2 is a key formula for mirror calculations.`},
{id:"c5n6",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"note",subtopic:"NEET Bridge — Total Internal Reflection & Lenses",content:`When light goes denser->rarer and the angle of incidence exceeds the CRITICAL ANGLE, all the light reflects back: TOTAL INTERNAL REFLECTION (TIR). TIR explains the sparkle of diamonds, a mirage, and how OPTICAL FIBRES carry light/signals — major NEET applications. Refraction through curved surfaces gives LENSES (convex/concave), governed by the lens formula 1/v - 1/u = 1/f and magnification, and by the human EYE (a convex-lens system; defects myopia/hypermetropia and their corrections are NEET favourites). Dispersion explains the rainbow and the prism spectrum.`,explanation:`The refraction you learn now (bending + critical angle) is the basis of optical fibres, the eye, cameras, and the whole ray-optics chapter in NEET.`,teacherTip:`TIR powers optical fibres and the diamond's sparkle.`,examTip:`NEET: critical angle, lens formula 1/v - 1/u = 1/f, and eye defects.`},
{id:"c5tf1",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Water is optically denser than glass.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Glass (mu ≈ 1.5) is optically denser than water (mu ≈ 1.33); light travels slower in glass.`,teacherTip:`Order: air (1.0) < water (1.33) < glass (1.5).`,examTip:`"Optical density" measures how much a medium slows light.`},
{id:"c5tf2",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"A ray of light going from glass to air bends towards the normal.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Glass -> air is denser -> rarer, so the ray bends AWAY from the normal.`,teacherTip:`DRA: Denser->Rarer = Away.`,examTip:`Draw the normal perpendicular to the surface first.`},
{id:"c5tf3",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The speed of light is greater in glass than in water.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Glass is denser than water, so light is SLOWER in glass (≈ 2 x 10^8 m/s) than in water (≈ 2.25 x 10^8 m/s).`,teacherTip:`Denser medium = slower light.`,examTip:`Speed is inversely related to refractive index.`},
{id:"c5tf4",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The depth of a pond seen from above appears less than its real depth.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. Light from the bottom bends away from the normal as it leaves the water into air, so the bottom appears raised — the pond looks shallower than it really is.`,teacherTip:`This is "apparent depth": pools look shallower than they are.`,examTip:`Apparent depth = real depth / refractive index.`},
{id:"c5tf5",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"A convex mirror is used as a shaving mirror.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. A CONCAVE mirror is used as a shaving mirror because, when the face is held close, it forms an enlarged, erect (virtual) image. A convex mirror is used as a rear-view mirror.`,teacherTip:`Shaving needs "zoom" -> concave.`,examTip:`Convex = rear-view (wide, diminished); concave = shaving (enlarged when close).`},
{id:"c5tf6",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"A concave mirror converges light rays, but a convex mirror diverges them.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. A concave mirror reflects rays inward to a focus (converging); a convex mirror reflects rays outward (diverging).`,teacherTip:`Converge = come together; diverge = drive apart.`,examTip:`Use arrows to show the direction of reflected rays in diagrams.`},
{id:"c5fb1",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Water is optically ______ than air.",blankAnswer:"denser",answer:`Water is optically denser than air (it slows light more, mu ≈ 1.33 vs 1.0 for air).`,teacherTip:`Rarer = thinner; denser = thicker (optically).`,examTip:`Write "optically denser" for physics accuracy.`},
{id:"c5fb2",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"When white light passes through a prism, it ______.",blankAnswer:"disperses",answer:`When white light passes through a prism it disperses into seven colours (VIBGYOR).`,teacherTip:`A prism is a "colour separator".`,examTip:`White light must fall obliquely (at an angle) for dispersion.`},
{id:"c5fb3",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The radius of curvature of a spherical mirror is ______ times its focal length.",blankAnswer:"two",answer:`Radius of curvature = 2 x focal length (R = 2f).`,teacherTip:`R = 2f. Use it to check your working.`,examTip:`State units (cm) when giving values for R or f.`},
{id:"c5fb4",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"A ______ mirror always forms a virtual, erect, diminished image.",blankAnswer:"convex",answer:`A convex mirror always forms a virtual, erect, diminished image (regardless of object distance).`,teacherTip:`Convex = "always small and upright".`,examTip:`This is why it gives a wide field of view as a rear-view mirror.`},
{id:"c5m1",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"match",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Match Column A with Column B",pairs:[{left:"Speed of light in vacuum",right:"3 x 10^8 m/s"},{left:"Refractive index of water",right:"1.33"},{left:"Concave mirror",right:"shaving mirror"},{left:"Convex mirror",right:"rear-view mirror"},{left:"Prism",right:"dispersion"}],answer:`Speed in vacuum->3 x 10^8 m/s, R.I. of water->1.33, Concave->shaving mirror, Convex->rear-view mirror, Prism->dispersion.`,teacherTip:`Match each optical item to its value or use.`,examTip:`Cross-check each pair before finalising.`},
{id:"c5mcq1",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The speed of light in air or vacuum is:",options:["3 x 10^8 m/s","2.25 x 10^8 m/s","2 x 10^8 m/s","3 x 10^6 m/s"],correctOption:0,answer:`3 x 10^8 m/s — a fundamental physical constant (about 300,000 km per second).`,teacherTip:`That's 300,000 km every second!`,examTip:`Units must be m/s.`},
{id:"c5mcq2",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The seven colours of sunlight in correct order from a prism are:",options:["VIBGYOR","ROYGBIV","BGYROVI","GYBRIOV"],correctOption:0,answer:`VIBGYOR — Violet, Indigo, Blue, Green, Yellow, Orange, Red.`,teacherTip:`"Roy G. Biv" reversed.`,examTip:`Violet bends most, red bends least.`},
{id:"c5mcq3",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Numerical",question:"If the radius of curvature of a concave mirror is 20 cm, its focal length is:",options:["10 cm","20 cm","40 cm","5 cm"],correctOption:0,answer:`f = R/2 = 20/2 = 10 cm.`,teacherTip:`Focal length is half the radius of curvature.`,examTip:`Include the unit (cm).`},
{id:"c5mcq4",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"A convex mirror is used:",options:["as a shaving mirror","in a torch","as a rear-view mirror by a driver","to focus sunlight"],correctOption:2,answer:`As a rear-view mirror — it gives a wide field of view with erect, diminished images.`,teacherTip:`"Objects in the mirror are closer than they appear."`,examTip:`Mention "wide field of view" as the reason.`},
{id:"c5mcq5",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Numerical",question:"Light travels through a medium of refractive index 1.5. Its speed in the medium is (speed in air = 3 x 10^8 m/s):",options:["4.5 x 10^8 m/s","2 x 10^8 m/s","3 x 10^8 m/s","1.5 x 10^8 m/s"],correctOption:1,answer:`mu = c(air) / v(medium), so v = c/mu = (3 x 10^8)/1.5 = 2 x 10^8 m/s (the speed in glass).`,teacherTip:`Speed in medium = speed in air / refractive index.`,examTip:`Higher mu -> lower speed.`},
{id:"c5ar1",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Assertion-Reason",question:"Assertion (A): A pencil partly dipped in water appears bent at the water surface. Reason (R): Light bends (refracts) as it passes between water and air because its speed changes.",options:["Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true, but R is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true"],correctOption:0,answer:`Both true and R explains A. Light from the submerged part changes speed at the water-air boundary and bends, so the pencil appears bent (an effect of refraction).`,teacherTip:`The "bent pencil" is the classic refraction demo.`,examTip:`Refraction occurs because light's SPEED changes at the boundary.`},
{id:"c5sa1",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"State the speed of light in (a) air (b) water (c) glass.",answer:`(a) Air/vacuum: 3 x 10^8 m/s\n(b) Water: 2.25 x 10^8 m/s\n(c) Glass: 2 x 10^8 m/s\n\nLight slows down as the medium gets optically denser.`,teacherTip:`Denser medium -> slower light.`,examTip:`Use 10^8 scientific notation with units m/s.`},
{id:"c5sa2",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"What is refraction of light? State the laws of refraction.",answer:`REFRACTION: the change in direction (bending) of light as it passes from one transparent medium to another, due to a change in its speed.\n\nLaws of refraction (Snell's laws):\n(i) The incident ray, the refracted ray and the normal at the point of incidence all lie in the same plane.\n(ii) sin(i) / sin(r) = constant = refractive index (mu) for the pair of media.`,teacherTip:`Refraction = bending at the boundary.`,examTip:`Both media must be transparent.`},
{id:"c5sa3",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"What is dispersion of light? Name the seven colours and state which bends most and least.",answer:`DISPERSION: the splitting of white light into its seven constituent colours when it passes through a prism.\n\nSeven colours (VIBGYOR): Violet, Indigo, Blue, Green, Yellow, Orange, Red.\n\nCause: different colours travel at slightly different speeds in glass, so they bend by different amounts. VIOLET bends the most (slowest in glass) and RED bends the least (fastest in glass).`,teacherTip:`Rainbows are natural dispersion.`,examTip:`Always state violet = most bent, red = least bent.`},
{id:"c5sa4",topicId:"ch5-light",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"HOTS / Application",question:"Why does a swimming pool appear shallower than it actually is, and why should a non-swimmer be warned about this?",answer:`Light rays from the bottom of the pool travel from water (denser) into air (rarer) and bend AWAY from the normal as they leave the surface. To an observer above, these rays seem to come from a point higher than the real bottom, so the bottom appears raised and the pool looks shallower than its real depth.\n\nRelationship: apparent depth = real depth / refractive index of water (about 1.33).\n\nSafety warning: because the water looks shallower than it is, a non-swimmer may misjudge the true depth and step or dive in, which can be dangerous. The real depth is always greater than it appears.`,teacherTip:`Apparent depth = real depth / mu; the bottom looks raised.`,examTip:`Link the refraction explanation to the practical safety point.`},
// ============================== CHAPTER 6: HEAT TRANSFER ==============================
{id:"c6n1",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"note",subtopic:"Heat Transfer Basics",content:`Heat is a form of energy that flows from a body at higher temperature to a body at lower temperature, until both reach the same temperature (thermal equilibrium). TEMPERATURE measures the degree of hotness (average kinetic energy of particles), while HEAT is the total thermal energy transferred. Effects of heating a body: (i) it expands, (ii) its temperature rises, (iii) it may change state.`,explanation:`Heat energy makes particles move/vibrate faster (more kinetic energy); cooling slows them down. Heat always flows hot -> cold on its own.`,teacherTip:`Heat = energy in transit; temperature = how hot (per particle).`,examTip:`Distinguish heat (total energy, joule) from temperature (hotness, degree C/K).`},
{id:"c6n2",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"note",subtopic:"Modes of Heat Transfer",content:`Heat travels in three ways: (1) CONDUCTION — transfer through a solid without the particles moving from place to place (vibrations pass on energy); metals are good conductors, wood/air are poor (insulators). (2) CONVECTION — transfer in fluids (liquids/gases) by the actual movement of heated particles (hot fluid rises, cool fluid sinks, setting up convection currents); e.g. boiling water, sea breeze, room heating. (3) RADIATION — transfer of heat as electromagnetic waves needing NO medium (it travels through vacuum); e.g. heat from the Sun, from a fire. Dark, dull surfaces are good absorbers/emitters; shiny, white surfaces are good reflectors.`,explanation:`Conduction = pass-it-on without moving (solids). Convection = particles physically carry heat (fluids). Radiation = heat rays through empty space (how the Sun warms us).`,teacherTip:`Conduction (solids), Convection (fluids), Radiation (vacuum/space).`,examTip:`Only RADIATION needs no medium; that is how the Sun's heat reaches Earth.`},
{id:"c6n3",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"note",subtopic:"Change of State",content:`MELTING: solid -> liquid at a fixed temperature (melting point of ice = 0 C).\nBOILING: liquid -> gas at a fixed temperature throughout the liquid (boiling point of water = 100 C at 1 atm).\nEVAPORATION: liquid -> gas at ALL temperatures, only from the surface; it causes COOLING (it takes latent heat from the surroundings).\nSUBLIMATION: solid -> gas directly.\nTemperature stays CONSTANT during a change of state because the heat supplied (latent heat) is used to break intermolecular bonds, not to raise temperature.`,explanation:`During a change of state, heat goes into rearranging particles, so the thermometer reading does not change until the change is complete.`,teacherTip:`Evaporation = slow, surface only, cooling. Boiling = fast, throughout, fixed temperature.`,examTip:`Distinguish boiling (fixed temperature, bulk) from evaporation (all temperatures, surface).`},
{id:"c6n4",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"note",subtopic:"Linear Expansion",content:`On heating, a solid expands. The increase in length depends on: (i) original length, (ii) rise in temperature, (iii) the material. Coefficient of linear expansion alpha = (Lt - L0) / (L0 x T). For the same material, alpha : beta : gamma = 1 : 2 : 3 (linear : superficial/area : cubical/volume). Different materials expand differently (brass expands more than iron), which is used in BIMETALLIC STRIPS (thermostats, fire alarms).`,explanation:`Heating gives particles more energy, so they vibrate more and push apart, increasing the spacing and hence the size.`,teacherTip:`Brass expands more than iron for the same heating.`,examTip:`Remember alpha : beta : gamma = 1 : 2 : 3.`},
{id:"c6n5",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"note",subtopic:"Expansion Order",content:`Order of thermal expansion: GASES > LIQUIDS > SOLIDS. Gases expand most because their particles have the weakest forces and the most freedom. Among liquids, alcohol expands more than water; among the listed solids, copper expands more than iron. NOTE the famous EXCEPTION — water shows ANOMALOUS expansion between 0 C and 4 C (it contracts on heating from 0 to 4 C, then expands), with maximum density at 4 C.`,explanation:`Weaker intermolecular forces let particles move apart more easily, so gases expand the most on heating.`,teacherTip:`Gases are the "expansion champions"; water is the odd one out (anomalous).`,examTip:`State the order Gas > Liquid > Solid, and mention water's anomalous behaviour.`},
{id:"c6n6",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"note",subtopic:"NEET Bridge — Specific & Latent Heat",content:`Two quantities you will use heavily in NEET: SPECIFIC HEAT CAPACITY (c) — heat to raise 1 kg of a substance by 1 C; Q = m x c x (delta T). LATENT HEAT (L) — heat absorbed/released during a change of state at constant temperature; Q = m x L (latent heat of fusion for melting, of vaporisation for boiling). Water's unusually high specific heat (4200 J/kg.C) moderates climate and makes it a good coolant. Evaporation causes cooling because the escaping molecules carry away latent heat — the principle behind sweating, earthen pots and refrigerators.`,explanation:`"Temperature stays constant during a change of state" is explained by latent heat; "different substances heat up at different rates" is explained by specific heat capacity.`,teacherTip:`Heating up: Q = mc(delta T). Changing state: Q = mL.`,examTip:`NEET: water c = 4200 J/kg.C; evaporation cools because it removes latent heat.`},
{id:"c6tf1",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Evaporation is rapid on a wet (humid) day.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. On a humid day the air already holds a lot of water vapour, so there is little room for more — evaporation is SLOWER. High humidity slows evaporation.`,teacherTip:`Humid air is a "crowded room" — fewer molecules can escape.`,examTip:`Evaporation rate decreases as humidity increases.`},
{id:"c6tf2",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Evaporation takes place only from the surface of a liquid.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. Evaporation is a surface phenomenon — only the molecules at the surface gain enough energy to escape into the air.`,teacherTip:`Surface only for evaporation; throughout the bulk for boiling.`,examTip:`Use the phrase "surface phenomenon".`},
{id:"c6tf3",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The temperature of a liquid rises during boiling.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. The temperature stays CONSTANT during boiling; the heat supplied is used as latent heat to change the state (liquid -> gas), not to raise temperature.`,teacherTip:`During a change of state the thermometer "freezes".`,examTip:`Name "latent heat" to explain the constant temperature.`},
{id:"c6tf4",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Solids expand the least and gases expand the most on being heated.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. Gases have the weakest intermolecular forces, so they expand most; solids have the strongest forces and expand least. Order: Gas > Liquid > Solid.`,teacherTip:`Weakest forces -> most expansion.`,examTip:`Quote the order Gas > Liquid > Solid.`},
{id:"c6tf5",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"All solids expand by the same amount when heated through the same rise in temperature.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Different solids have different coefficients of expansion; e.g. brass expands more than iron for the same temperature rise. This is why bimetallic strips bend.`,teacherTip:`Each material has its own "expansion personality".`,examTip:`Expansion depends on the nature of the material.`},
{id:"c6tf6",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Heat from the Sun reaches the Earth mainly by conduction.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. The space between the Sun and the Earth is a vacuum, so heat reaches us by RADIATION (electromagnetic waves), which needs no medium. Conduction and convection both need a material medium.`,teacherTip:`Vacuum in space -> only radiation works.`,examTip:`Radiation is the only mode that needs no medium.`},
{id:"c6fb1",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Boiling occurs at a ______ temperature.",blankAnswer:"fixed",answer:`Boiling occurs at a fixed temperature (e.g. water boils at 100 C at 1 atm).`,teacherTip:`Boiling = a "scheduled" event at a definite temperature.`,examTip:`Contrast with evaporation, which occurs at all temperatures.`},
{id:"c6fb2",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Evaporation takes place at ______ temperature.",blankAnswer:"all",answer:`Evaporation takes place at all temperatures (it is a continuous surface process).`,teacherTip:`Evaporation is a "24/7" process.`,examTip:`Use "all temperatures" to define evaporation.`},
{id:"c6fb3",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Gases expand ______ than liquids on heating.",blankAnswer:"more",answer:`Gases expand more than liquids (order: Gas > Liquid > Solid).`,teacherTip:`Gases are the expansion champions.`,examTip:`Quote the full order.`},
{id:"c6fb4",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Heat transfer that requires no medium is called ______.",blankAnswer:"radiation",answer:`Radiation — heat travels as electromagnetic waves and needs no medium (e.g. heat from the Sun or a fire).`,teacherTip:`Radiation works even through vacuum.`,examTip:`Conduction and convection need a medium; radiation does not.`},
{id:"c6m1",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"match",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Match Column A with Column B",pairs:[{left:"Conduction",right:"heat transfer in solids"},{left:"Convection",right:"heat transfer in fluids"},{left:"Radiation",right:"needs no medium"},{left:"Invar",right:"low expansion (pendulum/instruments)"},{left:"Pyrex glass",right:"low expansion cookware"}],answer:`Conduction->solids, Convection->fluids, Radiation->no medium, Invar->low expansion (precision instruments), Pyrex->low-expansion cookware.`,teacherTip:`Invar and Pyrex are chosen for their LOW expansion.`,examTip:`Pyrex resists cracking on heating because it expands very little.`},
{id:"c6mcq1",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"In evaporation:",options:["all the molecules escape","only surface molecules escape","the temperature of the liquid rises","molecules are pulled inward"],correctOption:1,answer:`Only the surface molecules escape — evaporation is a surface phenomenon and causes cooling.`,teacherTip:`Surface only for evaporation.`,examTip:`Distinguish surface (evaporation) from bulk (boiling).`},
{id:"c6mcq2",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The mode of heat transfer in which heated particles physically move and carry heat is:",options:["Conduction","Convection","Radiation","Sublimation"],correctOption:1,answer:`Convection — in fluids, warm (less dense) parts rise and cool (denser) parts sink, setting up convection currents that transport heat.`,teacherTip:`Convection = particles travel with the heat.`,examTip:`Convection only happens in fluids (liquids/gases).`},
{id:"c6ar1",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Assertion-Reason",question:"Assertion (A): Pouring some water on the body cools us on a hot day. Reason (R): Evaporation of water absorbs latent heat from the body, lowering its temperature.",options:["Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true, but R is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true"],correctOption:0,answer:`Both true and R explains A. Evaporating water takes its latent heat from the skin, so the body loses heat and feels cool — the same reason sweating cools us.`,teacherTip:`Evaporation causes cooling by removing latent heat.`,examTip:`Link cooling to latent heat absorbed during evaporation.`},
{id:"c6sa1",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Name and briefly describe the three modes of heat transfer.",answer:`(1) CONDUCTION: transfer of heat through a solid without the particles moving from place to place; energy passes by particle vibrations (metals are good conductors).\n\n(2) CONVECTION: transfer of heat in fluids (liquids/gases) by the actual movement of heated particles; hot fluid rises and cool fluid sinks, forming convection currents (e.g. boiling water, sea breeze).\n\n(3) RADIATION: transfer of heat as electromagnetic waves that need no medium (e.g. heat from the Sun reaching the Earth through vacuum).`,teacherTip:`Conduction = solids; convection = fluids; radiation = no medium.`,examTip:`Give one example for each mode.`},
{id:"c6sa2",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Differentiate between boiling and evaporation.",answer:`BOILING:\n- Occurs at a fixed temperature (boiling point).\n- Takes place throughout the bulk of the liquid.\n- A fast process; bubbles form.\n- Needs an external supply of heat.\n\nEVAPORATION:\n- Occurs at all temperatures.\n- Takes place only at the surface.\n- A slow, continuous process; no bubbles.\n- Causes cooling (absorbs latent heat from the surroundings).`,teacherTip:`Boiling = fixed temperature + bulk; evaporation = any temperature + surface + cooling.`,examTip:`Give at least 3 points of difference.`},
{id:"c6sa3",topicId:"ch6-heat",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"HOTS / Application",question:"Why does water kept in an earthen pot (matka) stay cool, even in hot weather?",answer:`An earthen pot has tiny pores in its walls. Water slowly seeps through these pores to the outer surface and EVAPORATES.\n\nEvaporation absorbs LATENT HEAT from the remaining water in the pot. Losing this heat lowers the temperature of the water inside, so it stays cool.\n\nThe effect is greater in hot, dry, breezy weather because evaporation is faster then. (The same evaporation-cooling principle explains why sweating cools the body.)`,teacherTip:`Porous pot -> seepage -> evaporation -> latent heat removed -> cooling.`,examTip:`Centre your answer on "evaporation absorbs latent heat".`},
// ============================== CHAPTER 7: SOUND ==============================
{id:"c7n1",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"note",subtopic:"Sound - Nature & Propagation",content:`SOUND is a form of energy that produces the sensation of hearing. It is produced by VIBRATING bodies and needs a MATERIAL MEDIUM to travel — it CANNOT travel through vacuum. Speed of sound: solids (fastest, ~5000 m/s in steel) > liquids (~1500 m/s in water) > gases (~330-340 m/s in air). Speed increases with temperature in a gas.`,explanation:`Sound needs particles to pass on the vibration, so in the vacuum of space there is total silence. Particles are closer in solids, so sound passes fastest there.`,teacherTip:`Solids are "fast lanes" for sound; vacuum is a dead end.`,examTip:`Memorise speed of sound in air ≈ 330-340 m/s; order solid > liquid > gas.`},
{id:"c7n2",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"note",subtopic:"Sound Wave Properties",content:`Sound travels as LONGITUDINAL waves (particles vibrate along the direction of travel, forming COMPRESSIONS — high pressure — and RAREFACTIONS — low pressure). Key terms: AMPLITUDE (maximum displacement from the mean position -> decides LOUDNESS); FREQUENCY f (vibrations per second, in hertz Hz; f = 1/T); WAVELENGTH (lambda) (distance between two consecutive compressions, in metres); TIME PERIOD T (time for one vibration, in seconds). WAVE EQUATION: v = f x lambda.`,explanation:`A compression is a squeezed (high-pressure) region; a rarefaction is a stretched (low-pressure) region. The relation v = f x lambda links speed, frequency and wavelength.`,teacherTip:`Amplitude = "height" of vibration; frequency = "how often" it vibrates.`,examTip:`Learn the wave equation v = f x lambda — it is a frequent numerical.`},
{id:"c7n3",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"note",subtopic:"Characteristics of Sound",content:`Three characteristics: (i) LOUDNESS — depends on amplitude; measured in decibel (dB); safe range 0-80 dB. (ii) PITCH — depends on frequency; higher frequency = higher (shriller) pitch. (iii) QUALITY/TIMBRE — depends on the waveform; lets us tell apart two instruments playing the same note. AUDIBLE RANGE for humans: 20 Hz to 20,000 Hz. Below 20 Hz = INFRASONIC; above 20,000 Hz = ULTRASONIC (used in SONAR, medical ultrasound and cleaning).`,explanation:`These three properties let us distinguish a whisper from a shout (loudness), a flute from a tuba (pitch), and a flute from a violin playing the same note (quality).`,teacherTip:`L-A, P-F: Loudness-Amplitude, Pitch-Frequency.`,examTip:`Human audible range = 20 Hz to 20 kHz; know infrasonic vs ultrasonic.`},
{id:"c7n4",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"note",subtopic:"NEET Bridge — Ultrasound, Echo & SONAR",content:`The wave ideas here open into NEET wave physics. v = f x lambda applies to all waves. An ECHO is a reflected sound heard distinctly when the obstacle is far enough (a delay of at least 0.1 s, so the reflector must be about 17 m away in air); distance = (speed x time)/2. ULTRASOUND (>20 kHz) is used in SONAR (measuring sea depth/locating objects), medical imaging (foetal scans, since it is non-ionising and safe), and cleaning/welding. In Class 11/NEET you meet resonance, the Doppler effect (apparent change in pitch when source/listener move) and beats.`,explanation:`The same v = f x lambda you use now governs echoes, SONAR and ultrasound imaging — all built on reflection of sound.`,teacherTip:`Echo distance = (speed x time)/2 (sound travels there AND back).`,examTip:`NEET: minimum echo delay 0.1 s; ultrasound applications; Doppler effect.`},
{id:"c7tf1",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"When sound propagates in air, it does not carry energy with it.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Sound IS a form of energy and carries energy through the medium by making particles vibrate (which is how it can move your eardrum).`,teacherTip:`No energy, no eardrum movement, no hearing.`,examTip:`All waves transport energy.`},
{id:"c7tf2",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"In a longitudinal wave, compressions and rarefactions are formed.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. Longitudinal (sound) waves consist of high-pressure compressions and low-pressure rarefactions along the direction of travel.`,teacherTip:`Compression = squeeze; rarefaction = stretch.`,examTip:`Mention both terms when describing sound waves.`},
{id:"c7tf3",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The frequency of a wave is measured in seconds.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Frequency is measured in hertz (Hz), i.e. vibrations per second. The second is the unit of time period.`,teacherTip:`Hz = 1/second.`,examTip:`Frequency -> Hz; time period -> s.`},
{id:"c7tf4",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The pitch of a sound depends on its frequency.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. Higher frequency gives a higher (shriller) pitch; pitch and frequency are directly related.`,teacherTip:`Faster vibrations = higher notes.`,examTip:`Pitch is directly proportional to frequency.`},
{id:"c7tf5",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Decibel is the unit of the pitch of a sound.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Decibel (dB) is the unit of LOUDNESS. Pitch is related to frequency, measured in hertz (Hz).`,teacherTip:`Decibel = volume; hertz = note.`,examTip:`Don't confuse loudness (dB) with pitch (Hz).`},
{id:"c7tf6",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Sounds above 20,000 Hz are called ultrasonic.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. Frequencies above the human audible range (above 20,000 Hz) are ultrasonic; below 20 Hz they are infrasonic.`,teacherTip:`Ultra = above; infra = below the audible range.`,examTip:`Audible range = 20 Hz to 20,000 Hz.`},
{id:"c7fb1",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The time period of a wave is 2 s. Its frequency is ______ Hz.",blankAnswer:"0.5",answer:`f = 1/T = 1/2 = 0.5 Hz.`,teacherTip:`f = 1/T.`,examTip:`Show the calculation f = 1/T for partial credit.`},
{id:"c7fb2",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"A tuning fork produces sound of ______ frequency.",blankAnswer:"single",answer:`A tuning fork produces a pure tone of a single frequency.`,teacherTip:`Tuning forks are "standard rulers" for sound frequency.`,examTip:`Use "pure tone" to describe a tuning fork.`},
{id:"c7fb3",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The human audible range of frequency is 20 Hz to ______ Hz.",blankAnswer:"20000",answer:`20 Hz to 20,000 Hz (20 kHz). Below this is infrasonic; above it is ultrasonic.`,teacherTip:`Remember 20 to 20,000 Hz.`,examTip:`State both limits of the audible range.`},
{id:"c7m1",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"match",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Match Column A with Column B",pairs:[{left:"Amplitude",right:"maximum displacement from mean position"},{left:"Frequency",right:"1/time period"},{left:"Loudness",right:"depends on amplitude"},{left:"Pitch",right:"depends on frequency"},{left:"Quality (timbre)",right:"depends on waveform"}],answer:`Amplitude->max displacement, Frequency->1/T, Loudness->amplitude, Pitch->frequency, Quality->waveform.`,teacherTip:`L-A, P-F: Loudness-Amplitude, Pitch-Frequency.`,examTip:`Cross-check each pair before finalising.`},
{id:"c7mcq1",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Sound cannot travel in:",options:["solid","liquid","gas","vacuum"],correctOption:3,answer:`Vacuum. Sound needs a material medium to travel, so it cannot pass through the vacuum of space.`,teacherTip:`In space, no one can hear you shout.`,examTip:`Vacuum is always the answer for "sound cannot travel".`},
{id:"c7mcq2",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The safe limit of loudness for audible sound is:",options:["0 to 80 dB","above 80 dB","exactly 120 dB","above 120 dB"],correctOption:0,answer:`0 to 80 dB. Sustained sound above 80 dB can damage hearing.`,teacherTip:`Above 80 dB = danger zone for the ears.`,examTip:`Memorise 80 dB as the safe upper limit.`},
{id:"c7mcq3",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Numerical",question:"A sound wave of frequency 500 Hz travels at 340 m/s in air. Its wavelength is:",options:["0.68 m","1.47 m","170,000 m","840 m"],correctOption:0,answer:`Using v = f x lambda, lambda = v/f = 340/500 = 0.68 m.`,teacherTip:`lambda = speed / frequency.`,examTip:`Rearrange v = f x lambda to find any one quantity.`},
{id:"c7ar1",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Assertion-Reason",question:"Assertion (A): An astronaut on the Moon cannot hear the sound of another astronaut directly through the surroundings. Reason (R): There is no air (medium) on the Moon, and sound cannot travel through vacuum.",options:["Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true, but R is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true"],correctOption:0,answer:`Both true and R explains A. The Moon has no atmosphere, so there is no medium to carry the longitudinal sound waves; astronauts use radios (electromagnetic waves) instead.`,teacherTip:`No medium = no sound.`,examTip:`Radio works in vacuum (EM wave); sound does not (needs medium).`},
{id:"c7sa1",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Define sound. How is it produced, and why can it not travel through vacuum?",answer:`Sound is a form of energy that produces the sensation of hearing. It is produced by the VIBRATION of a body.\n\nSound travels as LONGITUDINAL waves, which need a material medium (solid, liquid or gas) to carry the vibrations from particle to particle.\n\nIn a vacuum there are no particles to pass on the vibrations, so sound cannot travel through it.`,teacherTip:`Vibration produces sound; particles carry it.`,examTip:`Define sound as energy from a vibrating source that needs a medium.`},
{id:"c7sa2",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"State the three characteristics of sound and what each depends on.",answer:`(i) LOUDNESS — depends on the AMPLITUDE of the wave; unit: decibel (dB).\n(ii) PITCH — depends on the FREQUENCY; higher frequency = higher (shriller) pitch.\n(iii) QUALITY (TIMBRE) — depends on the WAVEFORM; it lets us distinguish different instruments playing the same note.`,teacherTip:`Big amplitude = loud; fast vibration = high pitch.`,examTip:`List all three with their dependence.`},
{id:"c7sa3",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Define amplitude, frequency, wavelength and time period. State the wave equation.",answer:`AMPLITUDE: maximum displacement of a particle from its mean position.\nFREQUENCY (f): number of vibrations per second; unit hertz (Hz); f = 1/T.\nWAVELENGTH (lambda): distance between two consecutive compressions (or rarefactions); unit metre.\nTIME PERIOD (T): time for one complete vibration; unit second; T = 1/f.\n\nWave equation: v = f x lambda (speed = frequency x wavelength).`,teacherTip:`Frequency and time period are inverses (f = 1/T).`,examTip:`Include units, and quote v = f x lambda.`},
{id:"c7sa4",topicId:"ch7-sound",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"HOTS / Application",question:"A ship sends an ultrasonic pulse to the sea bed and receives the echo after 4 s. If the speed of sound in water is 1500 m/s, find the depth of the sea. Name the technique.",answer:`The technique is SONAR (Sound Navigation And Ranging), which uses the echo of ultrasonic waves.\n\nThe pulse travels down to the sea bed AND back, so the total path = speed x time = 1500 m/s x 4 s = 6000 m.\n\nThe depth is half this distance (one way):\nDepth = (speed x time)/2 = 6000/2 = 3000 m.\n\nSo the sea is 3000 m (3 km) deep.`,teacherTip:`Echo travels there and back, so divide by 2.`,examTip:`Depth = (speed x time)/2; name SONAR and note it uses ultrasound.`},
// ============================== CHAPTER 8: ELECTRICITY ==============================
{id:"c8n1",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"note",subtopic:"Electric Current & Potential Difference",content:`ELECTRIC CURRENT is the rate of flow of charge (electrons): i = q/t. S.I. unit of current = ampere (A); of charge = coulomb (C). POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE (V) is the work done in moving a unit positive charge between two points: V = W/Q; unit = volt (V). Electrical energy W = V x i x t. Conventional current flows from + to - (opposite to electron flow).`,explanation:`Current is like water flowing through a pipe; potential difference is the "push" (provided by a cell/battery) that drives the flow.`,teacherTip:`A battery is a "pump" that pushes electrons round the circuit.`,examTip:`Write i = q/t and define each symbol.`},
{id:"c8n2",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"note",subtopic:"Power & Energy Units",content:`ELECTRIC POWER P = V x i = W/t; unit = watt (W); 1 W = 1 V x 1 A. Electrical ENERGY = V x i x t; S.I. unit = joule (J); COMMERCIAL unit = kilowatt-hour (kWh). 1 kWh = 3.6 x 10^6 J = 1 "unit" on the electricity bill. Energy consumed (kWh) = power (kW) x time (hours).`,explanation:`Power tells how fast an appliance uses energy; the kWh (the "unit") is what the electricity company charges for.`,teacherTip:`Power = energy per second.`,examTip:`Don't confuse kW (power) with kWh (energy).`},
{id:"c8n3",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"note",subtopic:"Power Transmission",content:`Electric power is generated at about 11 kV, then STEPPED UP to 132 kV (or higher) at the grid sub-station to minimise energy loss during long-distance transmission, then STEPPED DOWN in stages (e.g. to 33 kV at the main sub-station) and finally to 220 V for household supply. High voltage means lower current for the same power, which reduces heat loss (I^2 x R) in the wires.`,explanation:`Transmitting at high voltage keeps the current low, so far less energy is wasted as heat in the long cables; transformers step the voltage up and down.`,teacherTip:`Step up for distance, step down for safety.`,examTip:`Remember the sequence 11 kV -> 132 kV -> 33 kV -> 220 V.`},
{id:"c8n4",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"note",subtopic:"Safety Devices",content:`EARTHING: a safety connection of the metal body of an appliance to the ground (zero potential) via the earth wire; it protects from electric shock. FUSE: a short wire of HIGH resistance and LOW melting point connected in the LIVE wire; it melts and breaks the circuit when the current is too high. MCB (Miniature Circuit Breaker) is a modern reusable replacement. SHORT CIRCUIT: live wire touches the neutral wire (damaged insulation), causing a huge current. Colour code: Live = Red/Brown, Neutral = Black/Blue, Earth = Green/Yellow. Appliances are connected in PARALLEL.`,explanation:`A fuse "sacrifices itself" by melting to protect appliances and prevent fire; earthing sends any leaked current safely to the ground.`,teacherTip:`A fuse gives its life to save your TV!`,examTip:`Fuse wire = HIGH resistance + LOW melting point, in the LIVE wire.`},
{id:"c8n5",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"note",subtopic:"NEET Bridge — Ohm's Law & Resistance",content:`In Class 9-12/NEET, the central relation is OHM'S LAW: V = I x R, where R is RESISTANCE (unit: ohm, omega). Resistance depends on length, area of cross-section and material (R = rho x L/A, where rho is resistivity). This combines with the power formulas you have here: P = VI = I^2 x R = V^2/R. Resistors can be joined in SERIES (R = R1 + R2 + ...) or PARALLEL (1/R = 1/R1 + 1/R2 + ...). The heating of a wire (the basis of the fuse and electric heaters) is JOULE'S LAW OF HEATING: H = I^2 x R x t.`,explanation:`The "current, voltage, power" trio you use now is tied together by Ohm's law (V = IR) and Joule heating (H = I^2Rt) — the backbone of NEET current electricity.`,teacherTip:`V = IR is the master equation; P = VI = I^2R = V^2/R.`,examTip:`NEET: series adds resistances; parallel adds reciprocals; H = I^2Rt.`},
{id:"c8tf1",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"A fuse wire has a high melting point.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. A fuse wire has a LOW melting point (and high resistance), so it melts quickly when the current is too high, breaking the circuit.`,teacherTip:`Fuse = a "weak link" designed to break first.`,examTip:`State that the melting point is LOW.`},
{id:"c8tf2",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Flow of protons constitutes electric current.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. In a metallic conductor, electric current is the flow of ELECTRONS. Protons remain fixed in the nuclei.`,teacherTip:`Electrons move; protons stay put.`,examTip:`Define current as the rate of flow of electrons (charge).`},
{id:"c8tf3",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The S.I. unit and the commercial unit of electrical energy are the same.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. The S.I. unit is the joule (J); the commercial unit is the kilowatt-hour (kWh). 1 kWh = 3.6 x 10^6 J.`,teacherTip:`Joule for science, kWh for bills.`,examTip:`Remember 1 kWh = 3.6 x 10^6 J.`},
{id:"c8tf4",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Overloading of an electric circuit can lead to short circuiting.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. Overloaded wires get very hot, which can melt the insulation; bare wires may then touch, causing a short circuit (and fire).`,teacherTip:`Heat from overloading is the wire's worst enemy.`,examTip:`Link overloading -> melted insulation -> short circuit.`},
{id:"c8tf5",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The earth wire protects us from electric shock.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. The earth wire provides a safe, low-resistance path for any leaked current to flow into the ground instead of through a person's body.`,teacherTip:`Earth wire = "emergency exit" for stray current.`,examTip:`Earth wire connects to the metal body of the appliance.`},
{id:"c8tf6",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"A fuse is connected in the live wire.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. The fuse is placed in the LIVE wire so that, when it melts, the appliance is fully disconnected from the supply.`,teacherTip:`Safety devices (fuse, switch) go in the live wire.`,examTip:`Explain WHY: to cut power at the source side.`},
{id:"c8tf7",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"In a cable, the green (or green-yellow) wire is the live wire.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Green / green-yellow is the EARTH wire. The live wire is Red or Brown; the neutral is Black or Blue.`,teacherTip:`"Green is the Ground."`,examTip:`Live = Red/Brown, Neutral = Black/Blue, Earth = Green/Yellow.`},
{id:"c8fb1",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The unit in which we pay for electricity is the ______.",blankAnswer:"kWh",answer:`The commercial unit of electrical energy is the kilowatt-hour (kWh); 1 kWh = 1 "unit".`,teacherTip:`kWh = the "unit" on the bill.`,examTip:`Don't confuse kW (power) with kWh (energy).`},
{id:"c8fb2",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"1 kWh = ______ J.",blankAnswer:"3.6 x 10^6",answer:`1 kWh = 3,600,000 J = 3.6 x 10^6 J (= 1000 W x 3600 s).`,teacherTip:`3.6 million joules in one "unit".`,examTip:`Memorise this conversion.`},
{id:"c8fb3",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The colour of the earth wire is ______.",blankAnswer:"green",answer:`The earth wire is Green (or Green-Yellow).`,teacherTip:`"Green is the Ground."`,examTip:`Know all three colour codes.`},
{id:"c8fb4",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"A fuse wire should have high resistance and a ______ melting point.",blankAnswer:"low",answer:`A fuse wire should have high resistance and a LOW melting point, so it melts quickly to break the circuit.`,teacherTip:`Low melting point = melts fast on overload.`,examTip:`Both properties matter for a fuse.`},
{id:"c8m1",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"match",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Match Column A with Column B",pairs:[{left:"Current",right:"ampere (A)"},{left:"Charge",right:"coulomb (C)"},{left:"Potential difference",right:"volt (V)"},{left:"Power",right:"watt (W)"},{left:"Commercial energy",right:"kilowatt-hour (kWh)"}],answer:`Current->ampere, Charge->coulomb, Potential difference->volt, Power->watt, Commercial energy->kWh.`,teacherTip:`Match each electrical quantity to its unit.`,examTip:`Remember C-A-V-W-J units.`},
{id:"c8mcq1",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The S.I. unit of electric current is:",options:["volt","watt","ampere","ohm"],correctOption:2,answer:`Ampere (A). Current i = q/t.`,teacherTip:`"Amp" is short for ampere.`,examTip:`Don't pick volt (that's potential difference).`},
{id:"c8mcq2",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"1 kWh is equal to:",options:["3600 J","36000 J","360000 J","3600000 J"],correctOption:3,answer:`3,600,000 J = 3.6 x 10^6 J (1000 W x 3600 s).`,teacherTip:`1 kW x 3600 s = 3.6 million J.`,examTip:`Show 1000 x 3600 to get the number.`},
{id:"c8mcq3",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The voltage of the electricity supplied to our houses is about:",options:["11 kV","132 kV","33 kV","220 V"],correctOption:3,answer:`220 V — the standard safe voltage for household supply in India.`,teacherTip:`220 V is the home-supply number.`,examTip:`Know the full chain 11 -> 132 -> 33 kV -> 220 V.`},
{id:"c8mcq4",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Numerical",question:"A 100 W bulb runs for 10 hours. The energy consumed (in kWh) is:",options:["1 kWh","10 kWh","0.1 kWh","1000 kWh"],correctOption:0,answer:`Energy (kWh) = power (kW) x time (h) = 0.1 kW x 10 h = 1 kWh (= 1 unit).`,teacherTip:`Convert watts to kilowatts first (100 W = 0.1 kW).`,examTip:`Energy in kWh = kW x hours.`},
{id:"c8ar1",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Assertion-Reason",question:"Assertion (A): The fuse is connected in the live wire, not the neutral wire. Reason (R): Placing the fuse in the live wire ensures the appliance is disconnected from the high-potential supply when the fuse melts.",options:["Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true, but R is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true"],correctOption:0,answer:`Both true and R explains A. If the fuse were in the neutral wire, the appliance body could still be at a dangerous live potential even after the fuse melts; placing it in the live wire safely cuts off the supply.`,teacherTip:`Fuse in live wire = power cut at the source side.`,examTip:`Always justify the live-wire placement with the safety reason.`},
{id:"c8sa1",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Define electric current. State its S.I. unit and formula.",answer:`Electric current is the rate of flow of charge (electrons) through a conductor.\ni = q/t, where q = charge in coulombs and t = time in seconds.\nS.I. unit: ampere (A).`,teacherTip:`Current = "how fast" charge flows.`,examTip:`Write i = q/t and define each symbol.`},
{id:"c8sa2",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Define potential difference and power. State their units.",answer:`POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE: the work done in moving a unit positive charge from one point to another. V = W/Q. Unit: volt (V).\n\nPOWER: the rate of doing work / consuming energy. P = W/t = V x i. Unit: watt (W); 1 W = 1 V x 1 A.`,teacherTip:`Use the W-Q-V relationships to remember the formulas.`,examTip:`Keep time in seconds for the standard formula.`},
{id:"c8sa3",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"What is earthing? Why is it done?",answer:`Earthing is a safety measure in which the metal body of an appliance is connected by a thick wire to a metal plate buried deep in the moist earth, putting the body at zero (earth) potential.\n\nIf the live wire accidentally touches the metal body, the current flows safely through the low-resistance earth wire into the ground instead of through a person who touches the appliance, thereby preventing electric shock.`,teacherTip:`Earth = a giant sink that safely absorbs stray current.`,examTip:`State that earthing protects against electric shock.`},
{id:"c8sa4",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"What is a fuse? State two properties of fuse wire and where it is connected.",answer:`A FUSE is a safety device that limits the current in a circuit; it melts and breaks the circuit when the current exceeds a safe value.\n\nProperties of fuse wire:\n(i) High resistance.\n(ii) Low melting point.\n\nThe fuse is always connected in the LIVE wire so that the appliance is fully cut off from the supply when it melts.`,teacherTip:`A fuse sacrifices itself to protect the appliance.`,examTip:`Both properties (high resistance, low melting point) are needed for full marks.`},
{id:"c8sa5",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"What is short circuiting and overloading? How can they be prevented?",answer:`SHORT CIRCUITING: when the insulation is damaged and the live wire touches the neutral wire directly, the resistance becomes very low and a huge current flows, causing sparking and fire.\n\nOVERLOADING: when too many high-power appliances draw more current than the circuit is designed to carry, the wires overheat.\n\nPrevention: use a fuse or MCB in the live wire; use good insulation and wires of the correct thickness; and avoid plugging too many appliances into one socket.`,teacherTip:`Short circuit = accidental "shortcut"; overload = too much demand.`,examTip:`Define both and give the prevention methods.`},
{id:"c8sa6",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"State the colour coding of wires. Why are domestic appliances connected in parallel?",answer:`Colour coding:\n- Live wire: Red or Brown\n- Neutral wire: Black or Light Blue\n- Earth wire: Green or Green-Yellow\n\nAppliances are connected in PARALLEL because:\n(i) Each appliance receives the full supply voltage (220 V).\n(ii) Each can be switched on or off independently.\n(iii) If one appliance fails, the others keep working.`,teacherTip:`Parallel = full voltage + independent operation.`,examTip:`Give all three reasons for parallel connection.`},
{id:"c8sa7",topicId:"ch8-electricity",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"HOTS / Application",question:"Why is electric power transmitted over long distances at very high voltage?",answer:`Power P = V x I, so for a fixed amount of power, a HIGHER voltage means a LOWER current.\n\nThe energy wasted as heat in the transmission wires depends on the current as I^2 x R (Joule heating). Because this loss depends on the SQUARE of the current, reducing the current (by raising the voltage) sharply reduces the heat loss in the cables.\n\nTherefore power is stepped up to very high voltage (e.g. 132 kV) for long-distance transmission to minimise energy loss, and stepped down to a safe 220 V before reaching homes. (Step-up and step-down transformers do this.)`,teacherTip:`High V -> low I -> much less I^2R loss.`,examTip:`Centre the answer on the I^2R loss depending on current squared.`},
];
